The original dataset for this study was derived from the NHANES data collected between 2005 and 2018, which had been approved by the Ethics Review Committee of the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS)29. The NCHS Ethics Review Board (ERB) Protocol Number or Description corresponding to Survey Name and Date is shown in the " Ethics approval and consent to participate” section under “Declarations”. Prior to data collection, all participants or their guardians had signed written informed consent forms30. To ensure data integrity and accuracy, participants with missing data for heavy metal levels in blood or urine, renal function indicators (urine albumin, urine creatinine, serum creatinine, etc.), and inflammatory indicators (neutrophil count, monocyte count, and lymphocyte count) were excluded. In addition, we also excluded participants with missing values for covariates (such as ethnicity, alcohol consumption status, smoking status, blood pressure, blood glucose, etc.) and dietary data, as well as pregnant women (Fig. S1). After the aforementioned data preprocessing, a total of 9047 participants were included in the study. The estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) and proteinuria (Urine albumin/creatinine ratio, UACR) were used to assess the kidney function of the study population. The eGFR formula was as follows31:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
