## Introduction
Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) has become a major public health concern due to its high incidence, poor prognosis, and significant association with morbidity and mortality from non-communicable diseases1. Individuals with the glomerular filtration rate (GFR) below 60 mL/min/1.73 m² or the presence of kidney damage markers (such as proteinuria) are defined as CKD patients2. The global burden of CKD is increasing annually, and it is projected to become the fifth leading cause of death worldwide by 20401. Therefore, exploring ways to mitigate or eliminate modifiable risk factors for CKD risk is of particular importance. Exposure to environmental pollutants significantly increases the risk of CKD, with heavy metal pollution being of particular concern—among which cadmium (Cd), lead (Pb), and mercury (Hg) are prioritized for this study, based on three core lines of evidence: their strong kidney-targeted toxicity, widespread environmental presence, and well-documented associations with CKD pathogenesis3–5. Studies have shown that these heavy metals can cause acute and chronic kidney injury by disrupting kidney cell function, inducing oxidative stress, and damaging cellular structures6,7. More seriously, cadmium, lead, and mercury are widely used in industrial production and are characterized by environmental persistence and bioaccumulation8. These heavy metals accumulate in target organs such as the kidneys through biomagnification in the food chain9. Moreover, epidemiological studies have shown that individuals exposed long-term to environments contaminated with cadmium, lead, and other heavy metals have a significantly higher risk of developing CKD than the general population10. And, heavy metal pollution often occurs in combination, and combined exposure to heavy metals can have synergistic effects on kidney function, with toxicity levels reaching several times that of individual exposure11. Inflammatory responses are a defensive physiological mechanism of the body against injury or infection12. In recent years, an increasing number of studies have shown that heavy metal exposure can induce inflammatory responses, thereby increasing the risk of all-cause mortality13,14. For example, He et al. found that both individual and combined exposures to heavy metals significantly elevated systemic inflammation levels, based on data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES)13. Similarly, Zhao et al. demonstrated a strong correlation between elevated serum manganese levels and increased immune-inflammatory levels using data from 3,355 participants in Guangxi, China14. Meanwhile, patients with CKD often exhibit systemic inflammatory status15. Gu et al. further indicated that higher levels of systemic inflammatory responses in CKD patients are associated with increased mortality risk16. Therefore, we hypothesize that systemic inflammatory responses may mediate the association between heavy metal exposure and CKD. However, this hypothesis requires further investigation to be validated and elucidated. In addition, dietary patterns may play a significant modulatory role in the impact of heavy metals on CKD17. Studies often use standardized tools like the Dietary Inflammatory Index (DII) and the 2020 Healthy Eating Index (HEI-2020) to assess the relationship between dietary patterns and health outcomes18. The DII scores diets based on their pro-inflammatory or anti-inflammatory potential, reflecting the impact of food components on specific inflammatory biomarkers19. The HEI-2020 evaluates dietary quality by measuring adherence to recommended intake levels. A wealth of evidence supports the protective effects of healthy dietary patterns on kidney health20. Hu et al. conducted a cohort study that found individuals with kidney dysfunction who adhered to a healthier diet had significantly reduced mortality risk21. Relevant studies have also shown that healthy dietary patterns can significantly reduce the risk of chronic kidney disease by decreasing dietary acid load, oxidative stress, and inflammatory responses19,22,23. For example, nutrients abundant in plant-based diets, such as lutein and phytochemicals, can protect the kidneys by inhibiting inflammation-related signaling pathways24. Conversely, pro-inflammatory diets, typically rich in saturated and trans fats, refined carbohydrates, and high-salt foods, can activate inflammatory pathways and increase the risk of kidney function impairment25,26. These diets are linked to elevated levels of chronic inflammation markers like C-reactive protein and IL-6, which are key drivers of CKD progression26–28. Additionally, pro-inflammatory diets may lead to insulin resistance and endothelial dysfunction, further burdening the kidneys27. Exploring the potential relationship between heavy metal exposure, inflammatory responses, and kidney function decline, along with the modulating role of dietary patterns, is crucial. It reveals the mechanisms underlying the interplay between environmental and dietary factors and informs the development of dietary intervention strategies to mitigate the risk of heavy metal-induced kidney damage. To this end, this study utilizes cross-sectional data from seven consecutive cycles of the NHANES database from 2005 to 2018. This study integrates generalized linear models (GLM), restricted cubic spline models (RCS), weighted quantile sum regression models (WQS), and causal mediation models to explore the potential relationship between heavy metal exposure, inflammatory responses, and kidney function decline. Additionally, this study assesses the modulatory role of dietary patterns in this relationship using interaction models.

