## Determination of heavy metals
Cadmium, lead, and mercury can accumulate in the human body over the long term, with primary deposition in the kidneys. This bioaccumulation leads to a gradual increase in the concentration of these heavy metals in the body, thereby triggering chronic toxic effects. Numerous studies have shown a significant association between exposure to cadmium, lead, and mercury and kidney damage. In addition, epidemiological studies have also shown that people who are long-term exposed to environments contaminated with heavy metals such as cadmium and lead have a significantly higher risk of developing chronic kidney disease (CKD) than the general population. This study selected three common heavy metal pollutants (cadmium, lead, and mercury) for investigation. Given that kidney function encompasses multiple critical physiological functions, including filtration and excretion, this study selected indicators that included both blood levels of cadmium, lead, and mercury (reflecting heavy metal exposure and kidney filtration efficiency) and corresponding urine heavy metal levels (indicating kidney excretion capacity and clearance efficiency). This multidimensional indicator system aims to more accurately elucidate the complex relationship between heavy metal pollution and kidney function. The laboratory methods for measuring heavy metals are available on the NHANES website. The determination of blood heavy metal levels was performed by directly measuring whole blood specimens via mass spectrometry after simple dilution. Detailed laboratory procedures can be found in the relevant NHANES documents (wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nhanes/public/2017/labmethods/PBCD-J-PBY-J-R-MET-508.pdf). For urine samples, single random urine sample collection was adopted. Urine heavy metal levels were also directly measured by mass spectrometry following simple dilution. Detailed information on urine collection methods and laboratory procedures for urine heavy metal measurement can be accessed via the following NHANES links (https://wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nhanes/public/2015/labmethods/UTAS_UTASS_UM_UMS_I_MET.PDF, https://wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nhanes/public/2015/manuals/2016_MEC_Laboratory_Procedures_Manual.pdf).

## Definition of systemic inflammatory response
