## Dietary patterns
The DII and HEI-2020 are key indicators for evaluating an individual’s overall dietary inflammatory status and dietary health33. When used together, they provide a more precise assessment of diet quality and help explore the role of dietary patterns in the relationship between heavy metals and kidney function34. The DII focuses on the inflammatory potential of a diet. It is calculated based on an individual’s intake of 45 specific dietary components, including macronutrients, vitamins, minerals, flavonoids, and specific food components such as caffeine and curcumin26. Each component is assigned an “inflammatory effect score” based on the strength of the scientific evidence linking it to inflammatory biomarkers27. An individual’s intake is compared to a global standard database to obtain a z-score, which is then multiplied by the effect score and summed to yield a continuous score26,27. A negative score (the lower, the better) indicates an anti-inflammatory diet, while a positive score (the higher, the worse) suggests a pro-inflammatory diet25. The HEI-2020 assesses dietary adherence on based the latest Dietary Guidelines for Americans and comprises 13 components (nine adequacy components: total fruit, whole fruit, total vegetables, legumes/vegetables, whole grains, dairy, total protein foods, seafood/plant protein, fatty acids; and four moderation components: refined grains, sodium, added sugars, saturated fats)17,23. Adequacy component scores increase with higher intake up to a maximum, while moderation component scores increase with lower intake up to a maximum17. The total score, ranging from 0 to 100, is the sum of all component scores, with higher scores indicating greater adherence to healthy dietary recommendations23. In this study, both the DII and HEI-2020 indices were calculated using data from two 24-h dietary recall interviews provided by the NHANES database. The dietary data were standardized and the indices computed using the dietaryindex package in R.

## Biochemical parameters and quality controls
Fasting glucose was determined by the hexokinase method; glycated hemoglobin was isolated and quantified via high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC); serum cotinine was detected using isotope dilution high-performance liquid chromatography-tandem mass spectrometry (ID-HPLC-MS/MS) after extraction; triglycerides were measured by the GPO-POD enzymatic method; low-density lipoprotein content was mainly calculated using the Friedewald formula; and high-density lipoprotein content has been measured by the enzymatic method since 2013. Detailed laboratory measurement methods can be found in NHANES (https://wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nhanes/public/2015/labmethods/UTAS_UTASS_UM_UMS_I_MET.PDF). All laboratory data in this study were generated under the stringent quality assurance (QA) and quality control (QC) framework of the NHANES project. Regarding the internal laboratory analyses, QC measures were rigorously implemented: for urinary testing, the laboratory utilized negative and low-positive controls for monitoring at the start of each testing day and whenever a new reagent lot was introduced, with all critical parameters tracked via a dedicated software module. For blood CBC analysis, the laboratory adhered to a strict QC protocol, running commercial controls each shift and every 24 h, and maintained a comprehensive procedure for troubleshooting and corrective actions when controls were out of range. Simultaneously, NHANES has established overarching and rigorous QA/QC mechanisms throughout the entire process: QA activities cover critical steps such as equipment calibration and personnel training; while QC measures during data collection include automatic software editing and verification, data analysis of technician performance, and quality control for sample testing and processing to ensure survey accuracy. This multi-level, systematic QA/QC system collectively guarantees the high reliability and trustworthiness of all biomarker data in this study. Relevant details can be viewed on the NHANES website (https://wwwn.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/AnalyticGuidelines.aspx).

## Covariates
Given that eGFR calculation includes age and sex, which may introduce bias in the relationship between heavy metals and eGFR, and to ensure consistency in the relationship between heavy metals and UACR, this study excluded age and sex as covariates. Referring to relevant literature, this study ultimately included 12 covariates, categorized as sociodemographic factors: race, BMI (< 25 kg/m² for normal/underweight, ≥ 30 kg/m² for obesity, and the rest for overweight), rate of household income and poverty, and marital status; and health-related factors: physical activity (cycling or walking for ≥ 10 min per week), dietary supplement intake, alcohol consumption status (daily alcohol intake > 30 g for men or > 20 g for women), smoking status (serum cotinine ≥ 10 ng/mL), blood glucose (fasting glucose > 126 mg/dL or glycohemoglobin ≥ 6.5%), blood pressure (systolic pressure > 130 mm Hg or diastolic pressure > 85 mm Hg), blood lipids (triglycerides > 150 mg/dL, LDL > 100 mg/dL, HDL < 40 mg/dL for men or < 50 mg/dL for women), gout, and diabetes (based on medical history)35.

## Statistical analysis
This study used frequency (percentage) and mean (standard deviation) to describe categorical and continuous variables, respectively, and constructed a correlation plot (Fig. S2) to illustrate the relationships and distributions of blood heavy metals, urine heavy metals, SIRI, DII, HEI2020, eGFR, and UACR. To ensure the accuracy of the regression results and reduce the impact of extreme values, logarithmic transformations are applied to blood and urine heavy metals. First, GLM are used to examine the associations of individual blood and urine heavy metal exposures, SIRI, DII, and HEI2020 with eGFR and UACR. WQS regression models are used to determine the impacts of blood or urine heavy metal combined exposures on SIRI, eGFR, and UACR. RCS model is used to explore the exposure-response (E-R) relationships of blood or urine heavy metal individual or combined exposures, SIRI, DII, and HEI2020 with eGFR and UACR. To delve deeper into the study’s assumptions, we employed causal mediation analysis grounded in the counterfactual framework (executed via the mediation package in R) to evaluate the mediating role of SIRI in the associations between individual and mixed exposures to blood/urine heavy metals and eGFR/UACR. Additionally, we used moderation analysis models (constructed with the interactions package in R) to explore the moderating effects of DII and HEI-2020 in these associations. Finally, to validate the robustness of the study findings, participants are stratified into normal and abnormal kidney function groups based on whether eGFR was > 90 mL/min/1.73 m², and into proteinuria and non-proteinuria groups based on whether UACR was ≥ 30 mg/g. Subsequently, GLM are constructed to verify the relationships between blood or urine heavy metal individual or combined exposures, SIRI, DII, HEI2020, and the risks of kidney dysfunction and proteinuria.

