## Relationship of heavy metals in blood and urine on eGFR and UACR
As shown in Fig. 1a, blood cadmium, lead, and mercury are all associated with decreased eGFR. After adjusting for all covariates, each one-unit increase in the log-transformed levels of blood cadmium, lead, and mercury is associated with a decrease in eGFR of 5.22 (β = -5.22; 95% CI: -5.99, -4.45), 7.56 (β = -7.56; 95% CI: -8.30, -6.81), and 0.91 (β = -0.91; 95% CI: -1.43, -0.38), respectively. As shown in Fig. 1b, blood cadmium and lead are associated with increased UACR, while blood mercury is associated with decreased UACR. After adjusting for all covariates, each one-unit increase in the log-transformed levels of blood cadmium and lead is associated with an increase in UACR of 10.01 (95% CI: 0.21, 19.80) and 12.62 (95% CI: 3.74, 21.50), respectively, while blood mercury is associated with a decrease in UACR of 5.13 (β = -5.13; 95% CI: -9.43, -0.17). As shown in Fig. 1c, urine cadmium and lead are associated with decreased eGFR, while urine mercury is associated with increased eGFR. After adjusting for all covariates, each one-unit increase in the log-transformed levels of urine cadmium and lead is associated with a decrease in eGFR of 3.00 (β = -3.00; 95% CI: -3.51, -2.49) and 0.82 (β = -0.82; 95% CI: -1.37, -0.27), respectively, while urine mercury is associated with an increase in eGFR of 0.44 (95% CI: 0.03, 0.85). As shown in Fig. 1d, urine lead and mercury are associated with decreased UACR, while urine cadmium is associated with increased UACR. After adjusting for all covariates, each one-unit increase in the log-transformed levels of urine lead and mercury is associated with a decrease in UACR of 13.86 (β = -13.86; 95% CI: -20.29, -7.47) and 10.16 (β = -10.16; 95% CI: -15.56, -4.76), respectively, while urine cadmium is associated with an increase in UACR of 7.99 (95% CI: 1.62, 14.35). Fig. 1The relationship of heavy metals in blood and urine on eGFR and UACR. Notes The baseline model was not controlled for any covariates, adjusted model 1 was used to control for sociodemographic variables, and adjusted model 2 was used to control for all covariates. The same as follows. The relationship of heavy metals in blood and urine on eGFR and UACR. Notes The baseline model was not controlled for any covariates, adjusted model 1 was used to control for sociodemographic variables, and adjusted model 2 was used to control for all covariates. The same as follows.

## The E-R relationship of heavy metals in blood and urine on eGFR and UACR
As shown in Fig. 2, the exposure–response (E-R) functions of eGFR with log-transformed blood cadmium, lead, and mercury were all nonlinear (P for TOTAL < 0.05, P for Nonlinear < 0.05). The E-R relationship between log-transformed blood cadmium and eGFR was approximately U-shaped (decrease-increase), while the relationship between log-transformed blood lead and eGFR showed a decreasing trend. The E-R function between log-transformed blood mercury and eGFR showed a wave-like pattern (increase-decrease-increase). The E-R function of eGFR with log-transformed urine cadmium was nonlinear, while those with urine lead and mercury were linear (P for TOTAL < 0.05, P for Nonlinear > 0.05). The E-R relationships between log-transformed urine cadmium and lead with eGFR both showed decreasing trends, while the function between log-transformed urine mercury and eGFR showed an increasing trend. Fig. 2E-R relationship of heavy metals in blood and urine on eGFR. E-R relationship of heavy metals in blood and urine on eGFR. As shown in Fig. 3, the E-R function of UACR with log-transformed blood cadmium was nonlinear, while those with blood lead and mercury were linear. The E-R relationship between log-transformed blood cadmium and UACR was approximately U-shaped and wave-like (decrease-increase-decrease), while the relationship between log-transformed blood lead and UACR showed an increasing trend. The E-R function between log-transformed blood mercury and UACR showed an inverted U-shaped pattern (increase-decrease). The E-R functions of UACR with log-transformed urine cadmium, lead, and mercury were linear. The E-R relationship between log-transformed urine cadmium and UACR showed an increasing trend, while those for urine lead and mercury showed the opposite. Fig. 3E-R relationship of heavy metals in blood and urine on UACR. E-R relationship of heavy metals in blood and urine on UACR.

## Association of mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine with eGFR and UACR
As shown in Fig. 4, among blood heavy metals, lead had the greatest impact on eGFR (0.502), while cadmium had the greatest impact on UACR (0.640). In urine heavy metals, cadmium had the greatest impact on eGFR (0.463), while lead had the greatest impact on UACR (0.902). Fig. 4WQS weights of cadmium, lead and mercury in blood or urine on eGFR and UACR, respectively. WQS weights of cadmium, lead and mercury in blood or urine on eGFR and UACR, respectively. As shown in Fig. 5, combined exposure to blood heavy metals or urine heavy metals is associated with decreased eGFR. Moreover, combined exposure to blood heavy metals is associated with increased UACR, while combined exposure to urine heavy metals is associated with decreased UACR. After adjusting for all covariates, combined exposure to blood heavy metals is associated with a decrease in eGFR of 10.57 (β = -10.57; 95% CI: -11.57, -9.57), while combined exposure to urine heavy metals is associated with a decrease in eGFR of 3.04 (β = -3.04; 95% CI: -3.57, -2.51). Combined exposure to blood heavy metals is associated with an increase in UACR of 16.42 (95% CI: -3.047, 29.80), while combined exposure to urine heavy metals is associated with a decrease in UACR of 14.77 (β = -14.77; 95% CI: -21.63, -7.90). As shown in Fig. S3, the E-R functions of combined exposure to blood or urine heavy metals with eGFR were both nonlinear and showed decreasing trends. For UACR, the E-R function of combined exposure to blood heavy metals showed a linear increasing trend, while that of combined exposure to urine heavy metals showed a linear decreasing trend. Fig. 5Relationship of mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine on eGFR and UACR. Relationship of mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine on eGFR and UACR.

## Relationship between heavy metals in blood or urine and SIRI
As shown in Fig. 6, after adjusting for all covariates, log-transformed blood cadmium (β = 0.03; 95% CI: 0.00, 0.06) and blood lead (β = 0.04; 95% CI: 0.02, 0.07) are associated with increased SIRI, while blood mercury (β = -0.05; 95% CI: -0.07, -0.03) is associated with decreased SIRI. The relationship between urine cadmium and SIRI is not significant, while urine lead (β = -0.03; 95% CI: -0.05, -0.01) and urine mercury (β = -0.04; 95% CI: -0.06, -0.02) are associated with decreased SIRI. Combined exposure to blood heavy metals is associated with increased SIRI, while combined exposure to urine heavy metals is associated with decreased SIRI. Figure S4 shows that the E-R functions of blood cadmium and urine cadmium with SIRI are both U-shaped, indicating a decrease followed by an increase. The E-R functions of blood lead and blood mercury with SIRI show linear increasing and decreasing trends, respectively. The E-R functions of urine lead and urine mercury with SIRI show nonlinear increasing and decreasing trends, respectively. Additionally, Fig. S5 shows that the E-R functions of combined exposure to blood heavy metals with SIRI are nonlinear and showed increasing trends, while those of combined exposure to urine heavy metals with SIRI show decreasing followed by increasing trends. Fig. 6Relationship between single or mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine on SIRI. Relationship between single or mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine on SIRI.

## Relationship of SIRI, DII and HEI2020 with eGFR and UACR
As shown in Figs. 7, S6, and S7, both SIRI and DII are significantly associated with decreased eGFR and increased UACR. Conversely, higher HEI2020 scores are associated with increased eGFR and decreased UACR. After adjusting for all covariates, SIRI is associated with a decrease in eGFR of 2.74 (β = -2.74; 95% CI: -3.32, -2.16), while DII is associated with a decrease in eGFR of 0.71 (β = -0.71; 95% CI: -1.01, -0.41). SIRI and DII are also associated with increased UACR by 16.15 (95% CI: 9.36, 22.93) and 4.16 (95% CI: 0.53, 7.80), respectively. In contrast, HEI2020 is associated with an increase in eGFR of 1.99 (95% CI: 1.32, 2.67) and a decrease in UACR of 11.49 (β = -11.49; 95% CI: -20.33, -2.65). Fig. 7The impact of SIRI, DII and HEI2020 on eGFR and UACR. The impact of SIRI, DII and HEI2020 on eGFR and UACR.

## SIRI mediates the relationship between single or mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine and eGFR and UACR
As shown in Figs. 8 and S8, SIRI has significant mediating effects in the relationships between individual or combined exposures to blood or urine cadmium, lead, and mercury and eGFR or UACR. The mediating effects of SIRI in the relationships between blood cadmium, lead, and mercury and eGFR were 6.40% (95% CI: 4.91%, 7.16%), 11.29% (95% CI: 6.49%, 23.23%), and 13.46% (95% CI: 8.67%, 65.00%), respectively. The mediating effects of SIRI in the relationships between blood cadmium, lead, and mercury and UACR were 20.92% (95% CI: 11.56%, 68.10%), 7.67% (95% CI: 4.46%, 24.60%), and 14.85% (95% CI: 4.27%, 41.56%), respectively. The mediating effects of SIRI in the relationships between urine cadmium, lead, and mercury and eGFR were 3.55% (95% CI: 2.74%, 4.48%), 7.24% (95% CI: 3.64%, 8.97%), and 15.24% (95% CI: -91.99%, 45.37%), respectively. The mediating effects of SIRI in the relationships between urine cadmium, lead, and mercury and UACR were 5.88% (95% CI: 2.88%, 17.68%), -5.61% (95% CI: -6.78%, -2.35. Fig. 8SIRI mediates the effects of single or mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine on eGFR or UACR. SIRI mediates the effects of single or mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine on eGFR or UACR.

## DII and HEI2020 modulate the relationship between single or mixed exposure to heavy metals in blood or urine and eGFR and UACR
As shown in Fig. 9, the interactions between blood cadmium, blood lead, blood mercury and the DII significantly affect eGFR. Specifically, an increase in DII exacerbates the negative effects of blood cadmium and lead on eGFR, while the effect on blood mercury is not significant. Additionally, the interactions between urine cadmium and mercury and DII also significantly affect eGFR, indicating that DII enhances the effects of urine cadmium and mercury on eGFR. However, the interaction between urine lead and DII does not significantly affect eGFR. Figure S9 shows that an increase in DII significantly exacerbates the increase in UACR caused by blood lead and the decrease in UACR caused by urine mercury. Figure S10 indicates that DII increases the effects of combined exposure to blood heavy metals on the decrease in eGFR and the increase in UACR. Additionally, DII exacerbates the negative effects of combined exposure to urine heavy metals on eGFR. Fig. 9DII modulate the effects of heavy metals in blood or urine on eGFR. DII modulate the effects of heavy metals in blood or urine on eGFR. As shown in Fig. 10, HEI2020 has a positive effect on mitigating the negative impact of blood or urine cadmium on eGFR. Additionally, HEI2020 attenuates the potential promoting effect of urine mercury on eGFR. The interactions between other heavy metals and HEI2020 do not significantly affect eGFR. HEI2020 reduces the UACR decline caused by urine lead, but the interactions between other heavy metals and HEI2020 do not significantly affect UACR (Fig. S11). HEI2020 significantly mitigates the negative impact of combined exposure to blood heavy metals on eGFR (Fig. S12). Although HEI2020 reduces the UACR increase caused by combined exposure to blood heavy metals, this effect is not significant. Additionally, HEI2020 has a positive effect on mitigating the negative impact of combined exposure to urine heavy metals on eGFR but also attenuates the mitigating effect on UACR. Fig. 10HEI2020 modulate the effects of heavy metals in blood or urine on eGFR. HEI2020 modulate the effects of heavy metals in blood or urine on eGFR.

## Sensitivity analysis
The analyses in Figs. S13, S14, S15, and S16 show that exposure to blood cadmium and lead is significantly associated with an increased risk of kidney dysfunction. Additionally, exposure to blood heavy metals, except for mercury, is also associated with an increased risk of proteinuria. In contrast, exposure to urine heavy metals, except for cadmium, is associated with a reduced risk of proteinuria. Further analyses show that SIRI and DII are significantly associated with increased risks of kidney dysfunction and proteinuria, while HEI2020 is associated with a reduced risk of proteinuria. Notably, combined exposure to blood and urine heavy metals is also significantly associated with an increased risk of kidney dysfunction. These findings are consistent with the above results, indicating that the study conclusions are robust.

## Discussion
Heavy metal exposure poses a significant threat to human health, particularly kidney function. Therefore, it is crucial to explore ways to mitigate or eliminate the impact of heavy metals on the risk of CKD. Meanwhile, systemic inflammation and dietary patterns may play a role in the relationship between heavy metal exposure and kidney function, but the specific effects have not been fully explored. Therefore, this study, based on NHANES data, investigates the potential relationships between heavy metal exposure, inflammatory responses, and decreased kidney function, as well as the modulating effects of dietary patterns. This study utilized GLM, RCS, and WQS) to investigate the effects of individual and combined exposures to blood or urine heavy metals on eGFR and their E-R relationships, aiming to explore the nephrotoxicity of heavy metals and potential prognostic approaches. We found that individual exposure to blood heavy metals, combined exposure to blood heavy metals, and combined exposure to urine heavy metals were all associated with a nonlinear decline in eGFR. Urine cadmium and lead were negatively correlated with eGFR, with eGFR showing a nonlinear decline with increasing urine cadmium and a linear decline with increasing urine lead. eGFR increased linearly with increasing urine mercury. The findings that individual exposure to blood heavy metals, combined exposure to blood heavy metals, and combined exposure to urine heavy metals were negatively correlated with eGFR are consistent with previous studies36,37. However, the relationship between urine heavy metal exposure and eGFR is more complex and differs from previous findings. Jin R. et al. found a positive association between urine cadmium, lead, mercury, and eGFR using NHANES data from 2003 to 201238. A similar conclusion was reached by Sanders, A. P39. Interestingly, this study found that the relationships between blood or urine heavy metal exposures and UACR are also complex. Blood cadmium, lead, and combined blood heavy metals were positively correlated with UACR, with UACR increasing linearly with increasing blood lead and combined blood heavy metals, while the E-R function between blood cadmium and UACR showed a decrease-increase-decrease pattern. UACR increased linearly with increasing urine cadmium but decreased linearly with increasing urine lead, mercury, and combined urine heavy metals. These findings are consistent with those of Tsai et al., who found that high blood lead and high urine cadmium levels were significantly associated with proteinuria, further highlighting the potential role of heavy metal exposure in kidney damage and proteinuria40. Additionally, the relationships between urine cadmium, lead, and UACR are consistent with the findings of Yin et al. and Huang et al.41,42. WQS regression analysis reveals significant differences in the effects of blood and urine heavy metal mixtures on kidney function, with distinct biological mechanisms: in blood exposure, lead’s high weight (0.502) for eGFR arises from its direct activation of the glomerular NADPH oxidase-ROS pathway, inducing podocyte apoptosis, while cadmium’s dominant weight (0.640) for UACR stems from its specific downregulation of podocyte nephrin, disrupting the filtration barrier43–45. In urine exposure, cadmium’s leading weight (0.463) for eGFR reflects its chronic tubular accumulation inhibiting Na⁺-K⁺-ATPase, and lead’s extreme weight (0.902) for UACR unveils a “dose-dependent pseudo-protection” mechanism - low-dose urinary lead stimulates metallothionein to chelate free ions, reducing glomerular damage via antioxidant effects (echoing SIRI’s negative mediating effect of -5.61%)46,47. Mercury’s low weight in both matrices is due to its form-specific targeting (neurotropic organic mercury in blood, freely filtered organic mercury in urine that spares podocytes)48,49. In essence, blood mixture weights highlight acute glomerular inflammation and oxidative stress, while urine mixture weights reflect chronic cadmium accumulation and adaptive lead detoxification, functionally dissociating tubular and glomerular impacts. The complex relationships between blood or urine heavy metal exposures and eGFR and UACR may be related to the interplay of multiple mechanisms50. Blood or urine heavy metal concentrations may reflect different exposure time windows, with blood heavy metal levels more indicative of recent exposure due to significant influences from recent diet and environmental contact51,52, whereas urine heavy metals are closely related to long-term cumulative exposure50. Heavy metal excretion is a continuous process, and urine heavy metal levels can reflect the body’s cumulative burden over a longer period to some extent53,54. This difference in exposure time windows may lead to distinct characteristics in the relationships between blood and urine heavy metals and eGFR and UACR. Additionally, this may also be related to the fact that heavy metals can affect kidney function through multiple pathways and that different heavy metals have distinct nephrotoxicity pathways11,41,55. For example, cadmium primarily accumulates in the kidney cortex, causing proximal tubular injury, while lead mainly affects the glomerular filtration barrier through oxidative stress induction56–58. The differences between organic and inorganic forms of mercury may be associated with bidirectional biological effects47,59. Notably, UACR, as a sensitive indicator of glomerular injury, may be mechanistically dissociated from the filtration function reflected by eGFR, suggesting that heavy metal exposure may affect different kidney functional units through different pathophysiological pathways41,56,60. Moreover, antagonistic/synergistic interactions among metals and population-specific factors (such as systemic inflammatory status and nutritional status) may also be associated with kidney function impairment6,41,61,62. Numerous studies have revealed a significant association between heavy metal exposure and enhanced inflammatory responses in humans14. Further analyses indicate that intensified inflammatory responses not only negatively impact normal physiological functions but also significantly increase the risk of kidney dysfunction63–65. As an example, the research by Liu Qi et al. discovered that heavy metals can promote inflammatory responses, thereby increasing the risk of chronic kidney disease, particularly in women66. Moreover, the study conducted by Kuei-Hau Luo et al. also indicated that metal exposure might lead to kidney damage by affecting the inflammatory factor TNF-α67. Therefore, this study posits that long-term heavy metal exposure not only directly jeopardizes kidney health but also increases the risk of kidney dysfunction by inducing systemic inflammatory responses. The results of this study show that blood cadmium and lead are significantly associated with increased SIRI, while blood mercury and urine lead and mercury are significantly associated with decreased SIRI. Additionally, combined exposure to blood heavy metals significantly increases SIRI, while combined exposure to urine heavy metals shows a nonlinear trend of first decreasing and then increasing SIRI. Moreover, SIRI is associated with decreased eGFR and increased UACR. Subsequently, causal mediation models confirmed that SIRI significantly mediates the relationships between individual or combined exposures to blood and urine heavy metals and eGFR and UACR. This conclusion may be related to the multisystem toxicity of heavy metal exposure in humans52. The promotion of inflammatory responses by blood heavy metal exposure may be related to the oxidative stress and cytotoxicity they induce in the body9,68,69. Heavy metals may trigger systemic inflammatory responses by disrupting intracellular antioxidant systems, generating reactive oxygen species (ROS), and activating inflammatory signaling pathways7,68,70,71. In contrast, the inhibitory effects of urine heavy metal exposure on inflammatory responses may be related to kidney excretory functions and detoxification mechanisms for heavy metals38,72. As the primary organ for heavy metal excretion, the kidneys may reduce their toxicity in the body by excreting some heavy metals through urine72. When exposed to a single heavy metal, SIRI exhibits a positive mediating effect in the association between blood/urine heavy metals and eGFR/UACR. Nevertheless, upon combined exposure to blood heavy metals, this positive mediating effect of SIRI on eGFR (3.46%) and UACR (10.09%) is attenuated, which may be attributed to antagonistic interactions among metals or the saturation of inflammatory pathways73,74. Regarding combined exposure to urine heavy metals, a marked divergence in their impact on eGFR and UACR is observed: a weak positive mediation for eGFR (4.55%) and a strong negative mediation for UACR (-7.95%). This is in accordance with nonlinear toxicity mechanisms. At low concentrations, the kidneys’ excretory function takes the lead, and detoxification suppresses inflammation (resulting in an initial decrease in SIRI); however, when exposure levels rise, the cumulative toxicity of heavy metals surpasses the kidneys’ detoxification capacity, activating inflammatory responses and consequently inducing kidney impairment75,76. Overall, SIRI primarily amplifies inflammation in the relationship between single heavy metal exposure and kidney function indicators, particularly in blood heavy metal exposure. Yet, in combined exposure scenarios, especially with urine heavy metals, SIRI’s mediating role is regulated by both excretory detoxification and toxicity accumulation8,35. Urinary lead shows a negative mediation in both single and combined exposures, indicating it may ease inflammatory responses through temporary immune suppression or kidney compensation77. Also, the strong negative effect of combined urine heavy metal exposure on UACR (-7.95%) further supports the idea that low-dose heavy metals can trigger protective physiological responses. This pattern uncovers the multi-system interactive nature of heavy metal nephrotoxicity. On the one hand, heavy metals activate systemic inflammatory responses via oxidative stress, directly causing kidney damage; on the other hand, this effect is finely tuned by kidney excretion and dose-dependent detoxification mechanisms. This study constructed interaction models to further explore the role of population nutritional status (DII and HEI2020) in the relationship between heavy metal exposure and kidney function. An increase in DII exacerbates the negative impact of individual and combined heavy metal exposures on eGFR and the positive impact on UACR. Conversely, an increase in HEI2020 significantly alleviates the adverse effects of heavy metal exposure on kidney function. This may be related to the dietary characteristics reflected by DII and HEI2020 and their impact on systemic inflammatory responses and metabolic functions33,34. A higher DII dietary pattern may enhance the nephrotoxicity of heavy metals by exacerbating oxidative stress and inflammatory responses12,18. For example, pro-inflammatory diets may lead to elevated levels of inflammatory cytokines, thereby weakening the body’s detoxification capacity against heavy metals and the kidney’s self-repair ability, and further exacerbating the negative impact of heavy metal exposure on eGFR and the positive impact on UACR20,78. Conversely, a higher HEI-2020 dietary pattern is typically associated with diets rich in antioxidants, dietary fiber, and essential nutrients, which may mitigate the toxicity of heavy metals through multiple mechanisms79,80. For example, antioxidants can neutralize heavy metal-induced oxidative stress, dietary fiber aids in the excretion of heavy metals, and essential nutrients support the body’s metabolic functions and kidney repair capacity81,82. Therefore, an increase in HEI-2020 may alleviate the adverse effects of heavy metal exposure on kidney function by improving overall nutritional status and metabolic functions80. Additionally, the modulatory effects of DII and HEI-2020 on the relationship between heavy metal exposure and kidney function may also be related to their impact on the gut microbiota83–85. Pro-inflammatory diets may disrupt the balance of gut microbiota, leading to impaired gut barrier function and increased absorption and toxicity of heavy metals83. In contrast, healthy diets may help maintain gut microbiota homeostasis, enhance gut barrier function, and reduce the absorption and toxicity of heavy metals85. This study innovatively integrated blood (reflecting short-term exposure) and urine (reflecting long-term accumulation) heavy metal assessments to uncover their distinct impacts on kidney function indicators (eGFR and UACR). Using generalized linear models, restricted cubic splines, weighted quantile regression, and causal mediation models, we explored the “heavy metal exposure-inflammatory response-kidney function decline” pathway, revealing the complex mechanisms linking heavy metal exposure to kidney dysfunction via inflammation. We also employed moderation analysis models to assess dietary patterns’ role, finding that healthy diets may protect against heavy metal nephrotoxicity, while pro-inflammatory diets may exacerbate it. Consequently, reducing heavy metal exposure through environmental monitoring, targeting key inflammatory pathways in heavy metal nephrotoxicity, and promoting healthy diets constitute three vital evidence-based strategies for lowering the risk of kidney function impairment in exposed populations, holding great importance for public health improvement. However, this cross-sectional study has limitations. It cannot establish the temporal sequence of heavy metal exposure, inflammation, and chronic kidney disease, only allowing for the exploration of mediating effects between them; longitudinal studies are needed to clarify causality. Heavy metal exposure assessment relied on single blood/urine samples, which may not accurately reflect long-term exposure. Although acceptable due to heavy metals’ long half-lives, future research should use multiple samples or biomarkers for better long-term exposure assessment. The 24-h dietary recall method also has limitations, likely underestimating the associations between DII, HEI-2020, eGFR, UACR, and heavy metal exposure. Additionally, despite adjusting for key confounders using DAGs and multivariable models, unconsidered confounders might still influence results. Finally, the specific mechanisms of kidney function decline as a mediator remain unclear and require further laboratory investigation.

## Conclusion
This study found that individual and combined exposures to blood heavy metals were significantly associated with decreased eGFR and increased UACR, while individual and combined exposures to urine heavy metals were mainly associated with decreased eGFR and UACR. Additionally, SIRI mediated the relationship between heavy metal exposure in blood or urine and kidney function impairment. Dietary patterns (DII and HEI2020) played a modulatory role, with increased DII exacerbating the negative effects of heavy metals on kidney function, while HEI2020 had a mitigating effect.

